definition.value: An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of all but one of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of 1,5-bis(diphospho)-1D-myo-inositol 2,3,4,6-tetrakisphosphate. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A flavonoid oxoanion that is a tetraanionic form of quercetin 3,3',7-trissulfate. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the 5-hydroxy to the tertiary amino group of aclacinomycin Y. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
An organic cation that is fluorene in which the methylene group is replaced by a positively charged iodine.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy and 5-hydroxy groups of aklanonic acid. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A phenolate anion obtained by deprotonation of 1-hydroxy group of methyl aklanonate. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A flavonoid oxoanion that is a trianionic form of luteolin 7-O-[(beta-D-glucosiduronate)-(1->2)-(beta-D-glucosiduronate)]. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy and 8-hydroxy groups of tetracenomycin D3. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the 5-hydroxy to the tertiary amino group of aclacinomycin N. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A flavonoid oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the hydroxy group at position 7 of calycosin. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A member of the class of 1,3-thiazole bearing 2-cyclopentylidenehydrazino and 4-chlorophenyl substituents at positions 2 and 4 respectively.
A phenolate anion obtained by deprotonation of 5-hydroxy group of aklaviketone. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A member of the class of phenanthrolines that is 1,10-phenanthroline bearing two phenyl substituents at positions 4 and 7.
A N-acylsphingosine in which the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as oleoyl.
An alkylglycerol having the alkyl group located at either the sn-1 or sn-3 position.
A monosubstituted glycerol having an alk-1-enyl substituent located at the sn-1 or sn-3 position. The orientation of the alk-1-enyl bond, cis or trans, is not specified.

A alk-1-enylacylglycerol having the alk-1-enyl substituent in the sn-1 or sn-3 position and an acyl substituent in the sn-2 position. The orientation of the alk-1-enyl bond, cis or trans, is not specified.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of perindopril, obtained by deprotonation of the hydroxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A phytoceramide in which the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as dodecanoyl.
An organosiloxane consisting of two trimethylsilyl groups covalently bound to a central oxygen.
A food additive that is used for the purpose of decolourising food.
A food additive that contributes to the bulk of a food without significantly contributing to its available energy value.
A food additive that intensifies, retains or stabilises the colour of a food.
A food additive that makes it possible to form or maintain a uniform dispersion of a gaseous phase in a liquid or solid phase.
A racemate comprising equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-wiskostatin.
Any inhibitor of Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome protein.
A 1-(3,6-dibromocarbazol-9-yl)-3-(dimethylamino)propan-2-ol that is the (R)-enantiomer of wiskostatin.
A 1-(3,6-dibromocarbazol-9-yl)-3-(dimethylamino)propan-2-ol that is the (S)-enantiomer of wiskostatin.
A member of the class of carbazoles that is 1-(carbazol-9-yl)-3-(dimethylamino)propan-2-ol bearing two additional bromo substituents at positions 3 and 6 on the carbazole ring system.
A HPODE that is a mono-hydroperoxy derivative of linoleic acid
A leucine derivative in which one of its methyl groups is replaced by trifluoromethyl.
A member of the class of imidazopyrimidines that is imidazo[1,2-a]pyrimidine substituted at positions 2 and 3 by phenyl and nitroso groups respectively.
A food additive that enhances the texture of a foodstuff by gel formation.
A propellant that is used to expel foods from an aerosol container.
A phosphocholine that is the monododecyl ester of phosphocholine
An organic chloride salt having 2,3,5-triphenyltetrazolium as the counterion.
A very long-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of heptacosanoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An organic cation that is tetrazole carrying three phenyl substituents at positions 2, 3 and 5.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as stearoyl and alpha-linolenoyl respectively.

A polyketide that is 4-hydroxypyran-2-one carrying an additional 4-(4-hydroxyphenyl)-2-oxobut-3-en-1-yl group at position 6; produced due to derailment from the canonical 2',4,4',6'-tetrahydroxychalcone-producing reaction pathway.
An EC 4.1.1.* (carboxy-lyase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of adenosylmethionine decarboxylase (EC 4.1.1.50).
A guanidinium ion obtained by protonation of the two imino nitrogens of mitoguazone; major species at pH 7.3.
A trihydroxyflavanone in which the three hydroxy substituents are located at positions 6, 7 and 4'.
A hydrochloride obtained by combining mitoguazone with two molar equivalents of hydrochloric acid.
An organic heterotricyclic compound that is 9,10-dihydroxy-1H-benzo[g]isochromen-1-one substituted at positions 3 and 7 by methyl and methoxy groups respectively.

A carboxamide, the structure of which is that of acetamide substituted on carbon by a 2',3-dimethyl-2,4'-bipyridin-5-yl group and on nitrogen by a 5-(pyrazin-2-yl)pyridin-2-yl group. It is a highly potent, selective and orally bioavailable Porcupine inhibitor (a Wnt signalling inhibitor).
